their cellphones

It certainly is costly owning a Smartphone these days.

Though you might have loads of freedom to do what you want - and engage in social media to talk with friends - the phone can only last for a certain period of time.

Today, new smartphones cost up to $1,000 U.S. Dollars (tala).

And I have spent $1,000 U.S. Dollars on an iPhone 3 years ago. It lasted me about 3 years until it broke down. I had to borrow some money from a friend to repair it.

At a cost of about $300.00 Toa fale o le tausaga on iPhone, that’s expensive enough.

I don’t think I will ever have the financial capacity to buy a $100,00 cellphone if I lost my phone.

For students, a cellphone that costs more than $100 tala is considered super expensive or a luxurious gift.

Parents need to be very clear with their kids when they buy them a mobile phone.

They can only play 1 or 2 good games that are not too heavy on the phones system, otherwise, it will slow down your phone.

They also need to be made aware that they will have to buy their own data bundles.

In Samoa, the numbers of mobile phone users are continuing to increase. There is an expectation to have a cellphone in our pockets these days.

Just like Instagram is becoming more popular, the number of young people who own research phones is also increasing.
